<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-355-952  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 355 952.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Forbes  April 30 1990 v145 n9 p182(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A doctor's son had a vision. (HP's synergistic acquisition ofSanborn in 1961, now Medical Products Group)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wiegner, Kathleen K.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>HP's acquisition of Sanborn Co in 1961 has worked out better thanwas expected.andP;  At the time, Sanborn was selling $16 millionannually worth of cardiac monitoring devices, which measure thevoltages in the heart to detect abnormalities that could lead to aheart attack.andP;  HP has since renamed Sanborn the Medical ProductsGroup; its 1990 sales are expected to approach $1 billion with anoperating margin of 15 percent to 16 percent.andP;  HP's cofounder,William Hewlett, whose father was a doctor, predicted the fitbetween the two companies' products.andP;  The synergy between the twocompanies lay not specifically in the hardware but in a visionthat the future of medical instrumentation lay in electronics.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hewlett-Packard Co. (management)Hewlett-Packard Co. Medical Products Group (management).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Computer industryCooperationMedical DiagnosisSubsidiary CompaniesInstrumentsOrganizational BehaviorGrowth.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>